The search for "google-ai-edge gallery LlmChatModelHelper.kt "sendMessageAsync" callback "onMessage" "onDone" "onError" streaming kotlin full implementation" returned the following summary:
In the `google-ai-edge/gallery` project, the `LlmChatModelHelper.kt` serves as a wrapper to manage LLM interactions. The `sendMessageAsync` method utilizes a callback interface, typically defined as `MessageCallback`, to handle the streaming response[1][2].

Below is the standard pattern for implementing this callback to handle streaming output, completion, and errors as seen in the repository[2]:

### Implementation Pattern

```kotlin
// Example implementation of the callback in your ViewModel or UI Layer
llmChatModelHelper.sendMessageAsync(
    Contents.of(userMessage),
    object : MessageCallback {
        /**
         * Triggered when a new chunk (token/word) is received.
         */
        override fun onMessage(message: Message) {
            // message.toString() contains the accumulated text or the latest chunk
            // message.channels["thought"] can be used to extract "thinking" process if enabled
            resultListener(message.toString(), false, message.channels["thought"])
        }

        /**
         * Triggered when the full response generation is complete.
         */
        override fun onDone() {
            // Handle final UI state (e.g., re-enable send button, stop loading animations)
            resultListener("", true, null)
        }

        /**
         * Triggered when an error occurs or the process is interrupted.
         */
        override fun onError(throwable: Throwable) {
            if (throwable is CancellationException) {
                Log.i("LlmChatModelHelper", "The inference was cancelled.")
                resultListener("", true, null)
            } else {
                Log.e("LlmChatModelHelper", "Error during inference", throwable)
                // Handle error (e.g., show Toast or snackbar to user)
            }
        }
    }
)
```

### Key Components
*   **`onMessage(message: Message)`**: This is the core of the streaming experience. As the LLM generates text, this callback provides partial updates[2]. You should update your UI state (like a `StateFlow` or `MutableLiveData` list) with the contents of the `message` to show the "typewriter" effect[3][4].
*   **`onDone()`**: This is called once the model has finished generating the entire response. Use this to finalize the message status in your UI[2].
*   **`onError(throwable: Throwable)`**: Crucial for robustness. It distinguishes between a user-initiated cancellation (which should be handled gracefully) and actual runtime errors[2].

### Important Notes
*   **Migration**: The Google AI Edge team now recommends using **LiteRT-LM** (formerly associated with MediaPipe LLM Inference) for new Android projects[5][6]. If you are building a new application, ensure your dependencies are updated to the latest `com.google.mediapipe:tasks-genai` or the specific LiteRT-LM libraries as documented in the official [Google AI Edge guides](https://ai.google.dev/)[5][7].
*   **Performance**: Since LLM inference is resource-intensive, ensure your `sendMessageAsync` calls are managed within a scope that respects the lifecycle of your Activity or Fragment to prevent memory leaks and unnecessary processing when the user leaves the screen[3].

